<div style="display:none;">
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info1">
		<h3>Ashley – College Student</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/ashley-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you?</strong> 160,000 students miss school everyday do to the fear of being bullied, and every 7 minutes a child falls victim to bullying. People who are bullied are two times as likely to commit suicide and four times as likely to be diagnosis with clinical depression. These statistics along with my own personal experiences with being bullied are the driving force behind why I am so passionate bullying prevention.</p>
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you?</strong> I have been involved with PACER's since the age of 15. Bullying prevention is not a job for me, but a way of life.</p>
		<p><strong>Advice to prevent bullying?</strong> Speak up whether you’re the one being bullied or the one witness bullying tell someone right away, so that you can stop the bullying before it goes too far. Be a friend to someone in need kindness is the greatest medicine.</p>
		<p><strong>Your story?</strong> At a very young age I began to experience the harsh reality of bullying and I became the target for kids in school. By the age of 15 I promised myself that I would no longer be a target for bullies and created a platform titled "Bullying Stops Now," where I made it my mission to inspire other youth to speak up, and that together, we could put an end to bullying. In 2011 the ugly truth of what bullying leads to if not stopped became real to me. My brother Jay committed suicide. Although hard to bare, I found the positive and allowed it to inspire me to create a new platform entitled, "Raising Hope- promoting awareness, education on bullying and suicide prevention." I now use this platform to touch lives all across the state of Minnesota by telling my story and spreading my message of hope to all that are willing to receive it.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info2">
		<h3>Austin – 12th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/austin-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p>Bullying Prevention is important to me because I was bullied in middle school. I felt horrible and worthless because of it, and I even thought it was my fault. I later realized it was not my fault, and that I had no reason to blame myself for their action. Since then I have been standing up for others in my school and community. I do not want anyone to go through what I went through.</p> 
		<p>I live in Dothan Alabama and I am a part of my schools SADD Chapter which is the largest SADD Chapter in the US with 450 members. With SADD I have won the gold presidential volunteer service award twice in a row. This year I have already completed over 320 hours of community service in my community.</p>
		<p>I created an Anti-Bullying Campaign called i.AM. This campaign focuses on the positive in everyone's lives not the negative that the bullies try to go after. The goal of i.AM is to help others be proud of their unique qualities that make each and everyone special and wonderful. This Campaign has won a National Award last year for its unique way of going after bullying and making a difference in my community with a conference held at my school revolving around it.</p> 
		<p>My advice to preventing bullying in a school or even online is to take the bullies power away. At school ignore the bully, and tell a teacher if the person keeps coming after you. Never take the words of the bully literally those word mean nothing in the end. It is what you think of yourself that matters. At home through cyberbullying unfriend the person, block them, and you can even report them to the website officials. No one should make someone feel horrible for being who they are or being different, because different is good.</p>
    </div>	
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info3">
		<h3>Christina – 12th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/christina-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p>Nine hundred weekdays, one hundred eighty weekends, five years. Imagine being a victim for that many years, months, weeks, days, hours and seconds. I was a victim of bullying. I hesitate to use that word now, but for so many years, that is how I was defined. I was privately and publicly insulted, harassed and threatened. I was told by many to “do the world a favor and disappear for good.” As a result, I suffered with mental health and self esteem issues for many years. It was unbearable. Following eighth grade, I switched to the other middle school in my city, until the two schools joined together for high school. The bullying continued and even resulted in my younger sister being bullied by the sister of the girl who bullied me. I knew it was time for change.</p> 
		<p>This is the part of my story that I love to tell, especially when I am presenting to an audience. The overwhelming sense of sorrow in the room fades away. If you listen to me speak, this is the part where you hear the confidence in my voice for the first time. This is when you can see the pain in my eyes turn into strength, passion and desire. A sophomore English project on "passion" sparked change. I began working with PACER's National Bullying Prevention Center and there I found my voice. I have spent time speaking with our state representatives at the Capitol, I testified in front of our Senate committee in support of the Safe Schools For All Bill, I participated in bullying prevention documentaries, and I have spoken to many different leadership groups, media and organizations all around the country. The feeling I get when I hear the words, “you have helped me” is truly indescribable. I have finally found a way to turn every negative thing I have endured into something positive.</p> 
		<p>I have learned so many lessons from my experiences. If I could share just one with the world it would be the importance of sharing their stories. Stories not only provide us with our own sense of comfort, but with the ability to comfort others. An author once said, “stories are the only enchantment possible, for when we begin to see our suffering as a story, we are saved.” This quote by Anais Nin shows the importance of having a story, and sets the theme for my own. My story is unique and something I am very proud to share. Finding passion in something that tore me down for years has given me incredible strength to help others. I encourage everyone who has struggled to do the same.</p>
    </div>	
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info4">
		<h3>Hannah – 11th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/hannah-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>There is no reason to make someone feel sad, worthless, inferior, or anything of the type. Each person deserves kindness, care, and respect, and we all have a responsibility to maintain a safe environment for everyone.</p> 
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you? </strong>I love the color purple and I have three sisters!</p>
    </div>	
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info5">
		<h3>Ian – 4th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/ian-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>It’s important to me because I was bullied.</p>
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you? </strong>I have a cat that is 20 years old and I really like animals.</p>
    </div>		
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info6">
		<h3>Jacob – 12th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/jacob-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>For many years of my life I was bullied, because of this I have come to realize first hand the effects of bullying and how it harms a person. Therefore I never want any person to experience any feeling near how I felt when I was bullied. Bullying prevention is important because it is the first line of defense we have to keep kids safe from the torment of bullying. The second line is education in bullying prevention. We need to educate the students on bullying and the effects it has.</p> 
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you? </strong>I want people to know that I'm here, that I am fighting, because that's all I ever need to know. All I ever needed to know was there was someone who was there for me. I want all the kids being bullied to know that I'm here to help them. I want these students to know that they are not alone. I would also like to add that I believe that orange is more than just a color it is a statement. A statement I proudly make in my orange truck.</p> 
		<p><strong>Advice to prevent bullying? </strong>My advice to prevent bullying is tell someone, talk to someone, get help. Remember you can stand up for yourself. You are stronger than you think. Remember we all want to be ourselves so that means we have to accept others and let them be who they are too.</p>
		<p>I encourage everyone to share their story, and their experiences with others. Through sharing my story I believe I have not only helped myself deal with the tormenting things that happening to me, but I have also stood up and shouted for other victims to hear "You are not alone". </p>
    </div>	
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info7">
		<h3>Jules – 8th Grade</h3>
		<p>Jules Wagner (13) Valley View Middle School, Edina, MN</p>
		<p>Like most kids in the world we live in today, I was bullied. I had no self-confidence and no longer valued my life. I want to be the change I want to see in the world we live in today. If I am to have a son or a daughter one day, I want to be ensured that they can grow up in a society where being different isn’t frowned upon. No kid of any age should come home crying after a hard day of school of being humiliated, singled out, or abused. No kid of any age should dread going to school in the morning in fear of what may happen during the course of that day with their teachers or peers. These are things that I feared when I was just a little bit younger than I am today.</p>
		<p>I used to carry the negative words and the emotional as well as physical scars around with me day to day. Now, I carry my self confidence and passion to allow others to feel safe and welcomed at my school and every school across the world. They say everyone is created equal, but not everyone is treated equal and it has gone on for too long that differences have been shunned. I want everyone to celebrate differences and uniqueness.</p> 
		<p>My sister is my inspiration and my role model.  She was unfortunately bullied too, which breaks my heart to know that someone as amazing and beautiful and someone with such a compassionate soul as her could ever feel unwanted or unwelcomed by her peers and the adults in our community. That’s what sparked my passion. Her courage and her compassion for everyone who has felt the same as us. I now devote my time to extraordinary experiences where I advocate for bullying prevention, kindness, and self-confidence-and love. I take part in making my community a better place volunteering in my school’s special needs room, the Valley View Middle School: Student Leadership Team, and Where Everyone Belongs” Student Group and in leading my school’s Environmental Action Now! Club, also representing my school for the Edina Student Environmental Leadership Council.</p>
		<p>The reason why I take part in these groups is not only to get the satisfaction of first hand change but also benefiting the lives of kids in my community, city, and beyond for living in a better world tomorrow than the one I live in today.</p>
		<p>Love yourselves, and every other person, appreciate diversity, and stand up for not only the cause but for the outcome of future generations growing up in a world of acceptance and unity.</p> 
	</div>
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info8">
		<h3>Katie – 11th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/katie-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>I believe that bullying is such a common occurrence and affects everyone. I think that if everyone is affected by it, we should work together to eliminate it.</strong>  
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you: </strong>I'm a total musical theater nerd and my whole life practically revolves around it.  Secondly, I give great advice and love helping people fix their problems!</p>
		<p><strong>Advice to prevent bullying: </strong>I know it's cliché, but treat others how you want to be treated. Also, constantly ask yourself: is it necessary? If you're about to roll your eyes at someone or gossip, ask yourself that question.  Trust me, when it comes to bullying, your answer will always without fail be "no".</p> 
		<p><strong>Story: </strong>Both my sister and I have experienced different forms of bullying, especially during elementary school.  I think that the most hurtful and prominent were the subtle types, such as non-verbal or gossip.</p>
    </div>	 
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info9">
		<h3>Madison – 11th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/madison-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>As a victim myself, and a first-hand observer of the devastating impacts bullying can have on a person, I have made the commitment to do anything and everything in my power to make sure no one has to endure what I, and so many others, have had to go through.</p>
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you? </strong>I spent three weeks in various Haitian Refugee Villages in the Dominican Republic last summer, and I have a passion for public speaking.</p>
		<p><strong>Advice to prevent bullying? </strong>Never stay silent. I know it may sound redundant, but until you're in a situation in which you need help, you often don't realize how hard it is to ask for it. If you're being bullied, please confide in someone who can help, and if you observe bullying taking place, please help make your school a better place by telling a teacher or other trusted adult about what's transpiring.</p> 
		<p><strong>Your story? </strong>My best friend of three years confided in me that he identified himself as transgender, which had no impact on my perception of him in any way, but others didn't seem to feel the same way; his gender identity prompted confusion and a lack of understanding from his peers and ultimately contributed to his suicide. Although this was by far the most devastating experience of my life, it's greatly shaped who I am and how I go about my life; . It also provided me with a renewed appreciation for the tireless work and passion demonstrated by the staff of PACER each and every day - I'm so honored to have the opportunity to participate in and contribute to this organization and I'm constantly amazed by the lengths they go to ensure no one endures the strain of tragedy that bullying places on an individual and on society.</p>
    </div>	
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info10">
		<h3>Michelle – 8th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/michelle-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>Bullying is a very serious and depressing issue that kids all over the world face. Any person shouldn’t have to go through these hard situations. No matter what your race, religion, size, or personality is, you shouldn’t have to be treated terribly for it. That is why I think bullying prevention is very important.</p>
		<p><strong>Two things I want people to know about you? </strong>I love to play and watch basketball, and I love to travel.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bioInfo" id="info11">
		<h3>Olivia – 8th Grade</h3>
		<img src="/bullying/getinvolved/images/unityawardbios/olivia-bio.jpg" width="175" height="250" alt=""/>
		<p><strong>Why is bullying prevention important to you? </strong>I was bullied all through elementary school and I don’t want anyone to experience that kind of pain or to feel that they are all alone.</p> 
		<p><strong>Two things you want people to know about you? </strong>I started competing in natural pageants a year ago to build my self-esteem and make friends. As a result of my volunteering this past year, I earned The Gold President’s Volunteer Service Award for completing 125 hours of community service. That was such an honor.</p>
		<p><strong>Advice to prevent bullying? </strong>I have learned from talking to people that bullied me when I was younger, that there were certain things I did that triggered some of the bullying. I am not at all saying that it is my fault because bullying is never ok, but if I had known that when I was younger, maybe I could have changed the perception of my behavior.</p>
		<p><strong>Your Story? </strong>When I was in kindergarten, I struggled with a learning disorder and acted out in class due to frustration. The other kids saw I was different and would bully me. No matter what I did after that, the kids never accepted me. With some help from my parents and teachers, things got better for me academically, but I was still bullied and didn't have many friends. Luckily, I was able to turn to my parents for help. You should always tell your parents or another adult if you are bullied. </p>
		<p>I've been told I have thick skin, because I kept trying to make new friends even though it felt like I would never have any. In middle school, I finally have some good friends and they do not judge me based upon my behavior in Kindergarten. Because of my experience, I go out of my way to make kids feel accepted and I do not judge them because they are different. Now I have a lot of friends who support me in my stopping bullying effort and they accept me for who I am because I accept everyone for who they are. I don’t care what other people think of them because, to me, everyone is special on the inside no matter what they are on the outside.</p> 	
		<p>A year ago, I launched the Raise Your Crown Against Bullying initiative on Facebook and Instagram to help show other kids that are bullied that they are not alone. I also spend a lot of my volunteer time being an advocate for bullying prevention and awareness. I want every kid out there to know that bullying can happen to anyone, even adults. It is wrong, and everybody should be treated kindly. </p>
    </div>	
